00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
butterfly, but for some reason,  ideally due to the mutation of a  

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
single component they're now unable to fly.  And the geneticist would  

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
then say, ah-ha,  that component must matter an awful  

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
lot for the ability to fly because the butterfly that lacks that  

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:27.000
component cannot fly.  It's a totally complimentary point  

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.000
of view.  And the objects the geneticists  

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
study in order to do that are genes.  Now, what is of course hard for you  

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
guys to understand but will form a structure for some of the lectures  

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.000
that I'm going to give over the continuing part of this course,   

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
is that through most of the 20th century the folks who studied  

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
biochemistry and tried to understand proteins and the folks who studied  

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
genetics and tried to understand mutants had nothing to say to each  

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
other.  They didn't speak the same language.   

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
They had nothing to relate to each other by because there was no idea  

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
of how this gene stuff,  which started as a totally abstract  

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
business, could possibly relate to this protein stuff which started as  

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
a very practical in the test-tube thing.  And they went for a very  

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
long time as if they were just ships sailing in the dark unaware of each  

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
other.  And I exaggerate,  but it's more true than not.   

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:33.000
The great intellectual event was the unification of these two points  

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.000
of view through the discipline of molecular biology.   

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
Molecular biology was the discipline that realized,   

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
oh, my goodness,  these are two different sides of the  

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
same coin.  That,  in fact, genes encode proteins,   

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
proteins are encoded by genes.  Ah-ha.  This was a wonderful and  

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
important thunder clap in the 20th century.  Now,   

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
it was a theoretical piece of information at first.   

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
The idea that genes and proteins were related in this way was  

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
abstract, very important,  but you couldn't do anything really  

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
with it, because it turned out you couldn't actually work with  

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
individual genes.  The next great revolution of the  

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
20th century was a technological revolution that let you actually  

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
