00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
It was the result of extraordinary historical and economic forces over  

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:03.000
the course of about three centuries that culminated Mendel.   

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
Let me briefly explain why.  It starts with the Age of  

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
Exploration.  Europe starts sending out boats around the world,   

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
explorers to meet other parts of the world in the 1500s.   

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
The boats come back.  They bring back stories of amazing  

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
lands.  They also bring back odd plants, odd animals.   

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
People begin to look at these plants and animals.   

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
They begin to cross them,  grow them and cross them, and look  

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
at the weird odd combinations of things that are going on.   

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
And they say, wow,  there's so much more variation out  

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
in the world than we thought about.  Some of it's kind of useful.  We  

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
can make new kinds of varieties of plants different than we had before,   

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.000
new kinds of varieties of apples.  Now, it turns out that's not just an  

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
intellectual curiosity that that was the case because economics was  

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
changing in the face of Europe in the 1600s and in the 1700s with  

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:54.000
better transportation networks.  So if you happen to be able to make  

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
a better apple,  it was good, not just for your  

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
family, but you would be able to project that through lines of  

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.000
distribution to larger markets.  It became economically sensible to  

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:09.000
invest your efforts in producing a better crop because you could sell  

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:13.000
it to more people because unified markets and transportation systems  

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:17.000
were developing across Europe.  And, therefore, economic forces  

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
began to work toward getting a hold on the understanding of how you  

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.000
could do better breeding.  Now, this turned out to be  

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
particularly important to the folks in Central Europe in the  

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.000
Austro-Hungarian Empire,  which was the center of the textile  

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
industry.  They were particularly concerned,   

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
in the late 1700s, about the fact that as the center of the textile  

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
industry they had to be concerned about the raw materials like wool  

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:47.000
that they used.  Wool you could get from Central  

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Europe, the Spanish had begun producing by breeding better sheep  

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
with better wool.  This freaked out the guys in the  

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:58.000
Austro-Hungarian Empire because they were risking now losing this stuff  

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
to the Spanish because of their better sheep.   

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And they began,  around 1800, to say we better start  

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
understanding how to do breeding.  They put together societies to  

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.000
